<li id="cite_note-17"><b><a href="#cite_ref-17" title="">^</a></b> <a href="#CITEREFNumbers1992" title="">Numbers 1992</a>, p.&#160;18, noting that this applies to published or public skeptics. Many or most Christians may have held on to a literal six days of creation, but these views were rarely expressed in books and journals. Exceptions are also noted, such as literal interpretations published by Eleazar Lord (1788-1871) and David Nevins Lord (1792-1880). However, the observation that evolutionary critics had a relaxed interpretation of Genesis is supported by specifically enumerating: <a href="/wiki/Louis_Agassiz" title="Louis Agassiz">Louis Agassiz</a> (1807-1873); <a href="/wiki/Arnold_Henry_Guyot" title="Arnold Henry Guyot">Arnold Henry Guyot</a> (1807-1884); <a href="/wiki/John_William_Dawson" title="John William Dawson">John William Dawson</a> (1820-1899); Enoch Fitch Burr (1818-1907); George D. Armstrong (1813-1899); <a href="/wiki/Charles_Hodge" title="Charles Hodge">Charles Hodge</a>, theologian (1797-1878); <a href="/wiki/James_Dwight_Dana" title="James Dwight Dana">James Dwight Dana</a> (1813-1895); <a href="/wiki/Edward_Hitchcock" title="Edward Hitchcock">Edward Hitchcock</a>, clergyman and respected Amherst College geologist, (1793-1864); Reverend <a href="/w/index.php?title=Herbert_W._Morris&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Herbert W. Morris (page does not exist)">Herbert W. Morris</a> (1818-1897); H. L. Hastings (1833?-1899); Luther T. Townsend (1838-1922; <a href="/wiki/Alexander_Patterson" title="Alexander Patterson" class="mw-redirect">Alexander Patterson</a>, Presbyterian evangelist who published <i>The Other Side of Evolution Its Effects and Fallacy</i></li>
